{{Infobox person | name = Champa | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Chandrashekhar Patil | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1939|6|18|df=yes}} | birth_place = Hattimattur, Tq: Savanuru, Di: [[Haveri]], Karnataka | occupation = Writer, public intellectual, professor | movement = [[Bandaya movement]] | years_active = | nationality = Indian | education = [[Master of Arts|MA]] (Linguistics) | alma_mater = [[Central Institute of English and Foreign Languages|Central Institute of English and Foreign Languages (CIEFL)]], [[University of Leeds]] | notable works = ''Gandhi Smarane'' | spouse = | children = }}
'''Chandrashekar Patil''' (born 1939), popularly known as "Champa", is an Indian poet, playwright and public intellectual writing in [[Kannada]]. He is considered as one of the foremost voices of the [[Bandaya movement]].
Champa is the editor of the influential literary journal ''Sankramana'' started with two of his friends Siddalinga Pattanashetti and Giraddi Govindaraj in 1964. He is known for leading many social and literary movements such as [[Gokak agitation]], [[Bandaya movement]], anti-[[The Emergency (India)|Emergency]] agitation, agitation for the implementation of [[Mandal Commission|Mandal]] report, Farmer's movement, etc.
After retiring as professor of English from [[Karnatak University]], Patil served as the President of [[Kannada Sahitya Parishat]] and as the Chairman of Kannada Development Authority.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chandrashekar Patil|url=http://www.karnataka.com/personalities/chandrashekhar-patil-kannada-writer/|website=Karnataka.com|publisher=Oneindia.com|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> Protesting the assassination of his friend and Vachana scholar [[M. M. Kalburgi]], he recently returned his [[Pampa Award]], the highest literary honour of the [[government of Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kalburgi murder: Kannada writer to return Pampa award|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kalburgi-murder-kannada-writer-to-return-pampa-award/article7622303.ece|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=The Hindu|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref>
== Select bibliography == '''Poetry''' * ''Banuli'' (1960) * ''Madhyabindu'' * ''19 Kavanagalu'' * ''Gandhi smarane'' * ''Hoovu Hennu Taare'' * ''Shalmala Nanna Shalmala'' * ''Ardha Satyada Hudugi'' (1989; [[Karnataka Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry]])
'''Plays''' * ''Kodegalu'' * ''Appa'' (1969) * ''Gurtinavaru'' (1971) * ''Tingara Buddanna'' (1971) * ''Kattala Ratri'' * ''Gokarnada Goudasani'' (1974) * ''Nalakaviya Mastabhisheka'' (1979)
